1
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:10,419
How do you break the status quo?

2
00:00:10,919 --> 00:00:14,720
Pursue what you think is right and lead in a fight for the voiceless.

3
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:19,120
G'day, it's Luke Darson.

4
00:00:19,679 --> 00:00:24,760
The idea of self-improvement and leadership both on and off the field has been a lifelong passion of mine.

5
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:27,679
With one of my oldest friends, we created a leader collective.

6
00:00:28,079 --> 00:00:33,600
I've had the privilege of working with thousands of leaders in education, sport, industry and the arts

7
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:39,039
that have helped shift to what we see as the 21st century style of leadership where everyone has a voice.

8
00:00:39,939 --> 00:00:43,619
In this podcast, we hear stories from these iconic leaders.

9
00:00:45,100 --> 00:01:07,040
Today, I caught up with Professor Pat McGorry, a psychiatrist known worldwide for his development and advocacy for youth mental health services.

10
00:01:07,739 --> 00:01:13,739
In an environment which wasn't necessarily accepting of his passion, I talked to Pat about fighting for what's right

11
00:01:13,739 --> 00:01:17,620
and how he has led the way in saving millions of young Australian lives.

12
00:01:17,900 --> 00:01:25,579
Professor Patrick McGorry is a leading international researcher, clinician and advocate for youth mental health reform.

13
00:01:25,579 --> 00:01:31,079
He is the executive director of Origin Youth Health, a world-renowned mental health organisation for young people

14
00:01:31,079 --> 00:01:37,200
that has put Australia at the forefront of innovation in the prevention and treatment of mental illness.

15
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:41,760
Origin targets the needs of young people with emerging serious mental illness

16
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:47,340
and has become the model with which many youth mental health services use around the world.

17
00:01:47,900 --> 00:01:52,760
Pat McGorry is also a founding board member of Headspace, the National Youth Mental Health Foundation.

18
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:56,340
He believes that early intervention offers the greatest hope for recovery

19
00:01:56,340 --> 00:02:01,719
and therefore takes every opportunity to educate the community to recognise the early signs of mental illness

20
00:02:01,719 --> 00:02:04,060
without stigmatising or discriminating.

21
00:02:04,640 --> 00:02:09,319
His extraordinary 30-plus years of contribution to the improvement of youth mental health in this sector

22
00:02:09,319 --> 00:02:13,759
has transformed literally the lives of tens of thousands of young people all over the world

23
00:02:13,759 --> 00:02:17,860
and in 2010, his recognition for Pat's extraordinary life work, he was named.

24
00:02:17,900 --> 00:02:23,960
As the Australian of the Year, Pat, congratulations on a lifetime of contribution and achievement.

25
00:02:24,199 --> 00:02:29,199
I wanted to just start by saying thank you for your time in this important time, it seems, in the world.

26
00:02:29,300 --> 00:02:32,199
But firstly, where did the passion for youth mental health come from?

27
00:02:32,719 --> 00:02:39,719
Well, I remember when I was a young medical student, I was looking at the spectrum of medicine, really,

28
00:02:39,900 --> 00:02:46,759
and one of the areas that was, from a human rights point of view, that was so underserved and so neglected was mental illness.

29
00:02:46,759 --> 00:02:47,379
You know, people...

30
00:02:47,900 --> 00:02:51,639
In those days, we were locked away in, you know, mental hospitals, asylums,

31
00:02:51,780 --> 00:02:54,800
and it was like a 19th century approach, really,

32
00:02:54,979 --> 00:03:01,060
and I just felt that there are many areas of medicine you can work in,

33
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:05,819
and I did actually work for about four years in general medicine, in diabetes and those sorts of areas,

34
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,919
but really, you know, there was more than enough being done in those areas.

35
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:16,120
All of those areas were improving and, you know, well supported financially and with skill and talent,

36
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:17,120
but mental health...

37
00:03:17,900 --> 00:03:21,620
You know, it needed something very special to happen,

38
00:03:21,780 --> 00:03:24,139
and I thought maybe I could make a better contribution there.

39
00:03:24,479 --> 00:03:25,939
People tried to talk me out of it.

40
00:03:26,139 --> 00:03:28,080
They said, don't waste your life, you know,

41
00:03:28,479 --> 00:03:32,159
because the prejudice and stigma was even worse in those days,

42
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:34,900
and it's improved a lot in recent years.

43
00:03:35,439 --> 00:03:39,419
But actually, because it was coming up such a low base,

44
00:03:39,819 --> 00:03:43,000
we can make a huge difference if we improve things in that space.

45
00:03:43,020 --> 00:03:44,280
So that's what attracted me to it,

46
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:47,879
and I guess I felt an affinity for the suffering of the people, too,

47
00:03:47,900 --> 00:03:52,400
you know, the old school approach to medicine, the vocational sort of feeling about it.

48
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:54,080
I definitely think I had that,

49
00:03:54,219 --> 00:03:59,340
and I've been very lucky to have a lot of satisfaction and sort of reward

50
00:03:59,340 --> 00:04:04,900
from being able to work in an area where you see so many people benefiting and recovering,

51
00:04:05,759 --> 00:04:08,539
and they wouldn't have otherwise if you hadn't sort of put that effort in.

52
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:11,259
Yeah, I love the sense of empathy, Pat,

53
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:14,719
whenever I hear you talk about your genuine care for this space,

54
00:04:14,719 --> 00:04:17,500
and I did want to ask you that because I had read that that was the case,

55
00:04:17,899 --> 00:04:20,879
and your colleagues in the medical fraternity almost tried to talk you out of it

56
00:04:20,879 --> 00:04:24,100
and said, as you just quoted, then don't waste your time.

57
00:04:24,279 --> 00:04:26,740
This is not an area that needs that attention.

58
00:04:26,920 --> 00:04:30,160
So it was literally people said to you, don't worry about this space.

59
00:04:30,199 --> 00:04:31,920
Was that one of the things that came your way?

60
00:04:32,459 --> 00:04:37,560
Yeah, because I actually, without sort of promoting myself too much,

61
00:04:37,839 --> 00:04:41,560
I actually was â€“ I did quite well in my medical course,

62
00:04:41,560 --> 00:04:46,759
and I probably could have done â€“ I would have had the opportunity to do other things.

63
00:04:47,899 --> 00:04:52,220
If I wanted to, and people probably around me sort of probably saw that,

64
00:04:52,279 --> 00:04:54,300
and they said, well, why are you doing that?

65
00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:58,600
That's a waste of time, because they actually didn't see the people

66
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:00,579
with mental illness as fully human, I don't think.

67
00:05:00,720 --> 00:05:05,959
It was that bad, you know, and it's hard to imagine, in fact, these days, isn't it?

68
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,620
But that was the way they thought, and we still see that structural stigma

69
00:05:10,620 --> 00:05:15,800
in various areas, and the underfunding of mental health until just about now

70
00:05:15,800 --> 00:05:17,420
has been a result of that.

71
00:05:17,779 --> 00:05:17,819
Yeah.

72
00:05:17,819 --> 00:05:17,879
Yeah.

73
00:05:17,879 --> 00:05:17,899
Yeah.

74
00:05:17,899 --> 00:05:22,180
In medical research, even though, you know, we brought the biggest grants

75
00:05:22,180 --> 00:05:26,959
from the US and Europe into medical research in Australia in mental health,

76
00:05:27,439 --> 00:05:30,439
our colleagues in medical research tend to look down on our research

77
00:05:30,439 --> 00:05:31,980
as somehow not being as good as theirs.

78
00:05:32,139 --> 00:05:37,120
So there's still that sort of judgmental and stigma operating.

79
00:05:37,560 --> 00:05:38,879
Yeah, it's remarkable, isn't it?

80
00:05:38,939 --> 00:05:43,680
And we're all thankful, Pat, and so many are, that you used your skills this way.

81
00:05:43,680 --> 00:05:47,639
You did qualify as a surgeon and a doctor, and you went down this path.

82
00:05:47,639 --> 00:05:53,699
But can I ask you, I feel like there is clearly in 2021 and now an understanding

83
00:05:53,699 --> 00:05:58,879
for those that probably generally are well and haven't suffered a medical illness

84
00:05:58,879 --> 00:06:03,220
in the mental health space, that they have an understanding of you need to do things

85
00:06:03,220 --> 00:06:05,079
to protect and better your mental health.

86
00:06:05,160 --> 00:06:07,879
I don't think a lot of people had made that connection until recently.

87
00:06:08,040 --> 00:06:09,639
Is that a fair thing to say, Pat, in your mind?

88
00:06:10,060 --> 00:06:12,639
Yeah, that's a very astute observation, Luke, I reckon.

89
00:06:13,180 --> 00:06:17,560
And that's one of the benefits of the pandemic, even though it's unleashed a shadow pandemic,

90
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:22,980
on us with another 25% of people needing professional help for mental ill health.

91
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:28,120
It's sensitized the whole population, whether it's, you know, just watching our kids,

92
00:06:28,259 --> 00:06:33,000
our teenagers and our young adult kids struggle, because they've borne the big burden

93
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,600
of the pandemic, really, or it's ourselves.

94
00:06:36,779 --> 00:06:40,839
I mean, maybe we haven't become, you know, seriously mentally ill as a result of the pandemic,

95
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,680
most of us, thank God, but many of us actually got pretty close to the edge

96
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:46,600
of the precipice there.

97
00:06:47,079 --> 00:06:50,220
And all of us have suffered a loss of well-being and morale, I think.

98
00:06:50,279 --> 00:06:55,180
We've all lost the sort of access to things that make life worth living during the last

99
00:06:55,180 --> 00:06:56,660
18 months or so, especially in Melbourne.

100
00:06:57,160 --> 00:07:02,060
And so we feel it, you know, we know, we've got a better idea of what it feels

101
00:07:02,060 --> 00:07:04,220
to lose mental health.

102
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:07,980
And when you turn for help, you can't access it at the moment.

103
00:07:08,220 --> 00:07:13,079
It's very difficult to access, and the quality of it isn't what it could be, I suppose.

104
00:07:13,079 --> 00:07:16,079
So I think it's great to have the public sort of...

105
00:07:16,600 --> 00:07:17,500
What's the word?

106
00:07:17,879 --> 00:07:20,939
They've had awareness for years in a superficial sense, I mean,

107
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:22,879
but they haven't really felt it.

108
00:07:22,980 --> 00:07:26,339
They haven't, you know, I think in a deeper way, like you're alluding to, yeah.

109
00:07:26,720 --> 00:07:28,240
Yeah, I might jump into that, Pat.

110
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:34,980
The term shadow pandemic was a really profound use of words that you really brought

111
00:07:34,980 --> 00:07:36,819
to people's attention around what was going on.

112
00:07:36,860 --> 00:07:39,079
And it's hard to ignore you and I both living in Melbourne,

113
00:07:39,139 --> 00:07:42,519
and for those listening around the country or elsewhere in the world,

114
00:07:42,519 --> 00:07:45,959
it is the record for the most locked down city in the world, Melbourne.

115
00:07:45,959 --> 00:07:48,920
And tragically and unfortunately, and it felt to me, Pat,

116
00:07:48,959 --> 00:07:52,060
in some ways as a perfect storm for our youth.

117
00:07:52,139 --> 00:07:55,959
And clearly, you're at the coalface of this and you've seen a 25% increase.

118
00:07:56,139 --> 00:08:00,560
But there is, you know, even watching my own household full of teenagers

119
00:08:00,560 --> 00:08:03,720
and your own kids and their friends just to see the impact, Pat.

120
00:08:03,899 --> 00:08:06,540
There are some numbers that I can't get out of my brain, Pat,

121
00:08:06,600 --> 00:08:08,519
that you'll probably be able to clarify.

122
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:12,300
But Damon Johnson, the Australian, was reporting several weeks ago

123
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:14,819
that at the peak of this last lockdown in Melbourne,

124
00:08:14,819 --> 00:08:15,779
there was 830.

125
00:08:15,959 --> 00:08:18,759
Eating disorders diagnosed a week in Melbourne.

126
00:08:19,319 --> 00:08:23,699
In one city, there was 350 of our teenagers presenting at emergency

127
00:08:23,699 --> 00:08:26,759
because their families were so concerned about the fact

128
00:08:26,759 --> 00:08:27,819
they may take their own lives.

129
00:08:27,899 --> 00:08:31,740
There was a couple of hundred a week who were self-harming in regularness.

130
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:35,480
In that sort of numbers, as you said, a shadow pandemic

131
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:37,659
that wasn't being spoken about or discussed.

132
00:08:37,860 --> 00:08:41,360
What advice have you got for parents that have been generally concerned

133
00:08:41,360 --> 00:08:42,960
about their kids through this time?

134
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:44,919
What are some practical things that parents can do, Pat?

135
00:08:45,960 --> 00:08:48,299
On the numbers, before we get into that,

136
00:08:49,440 --> 00:08:53,720
we run five headspace centres across the North West through Origin

137
00:08:53,720 --> 00:08:58,139
and we run the state specialist mental health system at Origin too.

138
00:08:58,299 --> 00:08:59,460
There's a backup system to that.

139
00:08:59,799 --> 00:09:02,779
We've got about 1,000 young people on our waiting list

140
00:09:02,779 --> 00:09:07,059
who can't get into our system because it's just not built to scale yet.

141
00:09:07,879 --> 00:09:12,460
And as you say, a lot of that is young people, young women quite often

142
00:09:12,460 --> 00:09:15,799
with an emerging eating disorder like anorexia nervosa.

143
00:09:15,960 --> 00:09:21,960
Or combinations of that with anxiety, depression and often a lot of self-harm

144
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:26,320
because they've discovered that that's a way of alleviating

145
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:27,820
the emotional pain temporarily.

146
00:09:28,139 --> 00:09:31,299
It's kind of a very disturbing thing, isn't it,

147
00:09:31,299 --> 00:09:34,639
when you see people cutting themselves to relieve emotional pain.

148
00:09:34,860 --> 00:09:37,600
Parents really freak out when they see that happening quite rightly.

149
00:09:38,039 --> 00:09:40,580
But it shows how desperate the situation is.

150
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:42,840
So that's what we're dealing with on a day-to-day basis.

151
00:09:43,299 --> 00:09:45,580
And in terms of what...

152
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:49,179
And I suppose the first thing is recognition.

153
00:09:49,580 --> 00:09:53,120
And you don't want to kind of, I suppose, panic.

154
00:09:54,179 --> 00:09:58,860
Just because your teenager is having a bad day, you don't want to overreact

155
00:09:58,860 --> 00:10:02,600
because it's an emotionally challenging time growing up

156
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:05,200
and working out who you are and dealing with bullying

157
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:07,139
and peer groups and all that sort of stuff.

158
00:10:07,279 --> 00:10:08,220
We all have to do it.

159
00:10:08,299 --> 00:10:12,700
But 50% of the young people as they navigate that transition to adult life

160
00:10:12,700 --> 00:10:14,419
will have a period of poor mental health.

161
00:10:14,639 --> 00:10:15,940
So it's not like we're...

162
00:10:15,960 --> 00:10:17,480
Medicalising it is just a reality.

163
00:10:17,759 --> 00:10:19,440
And what we've got to do is help those kids

164
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:21,419
because if they're not helped, you know,

165
00:10:21,440 --> 00:10:23,779
it's the biggest cause of death in young people

166
00:10:23,779 --> 00:10:26,080
up to the age of even 40 is suicide.

167
00:10:26,879 --> 00:10:30,679
And it's certainly by far the biggest cause of disability

168
00:10:30,679 --> 00:10:33,700
or not fulfilling your potential as a human being

169
00:10:33,700 --> 00:10:35,980
if you have untreated mental ill health.

170
00:10:36,299 --> 00:10:39,159
Often it's quite obvious that the young person has become more withdrawn,

171
00:10:39,159 --> 00:10:40,559
they're not going so well at school,

172
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:43,259
they're not so much in contact with their friends

173
00:10:43,259 --> 00:10:45,759
or they're angry and irritable.

174
00:10:45,960 --> 00:10:48,899
Not just on a one-off,

175
00:10:49,019 --> 00:10:53,940
but just a sustained, you know, irritability, anger and distress.

176
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:56,360
You know, I mean, you can see the distress.

177
00:10:56,659 --> 00:10:59,679
Now, obviously, more obvious things like weight loss in a young woman,

178
00:10:59,860 --> 00:11:01,879
that's a warning sign.

179
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,059
So if parents are worried, they should definitely educate themselves

180
00:11:05,059 --> 00:11:09,379
and also try to access help.

181
00:11:10,700 --> 00:11:13,440
The parents will have been affected badly by the pandemic.

182
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:15,340
Parents will have suffered.

183
00:11:15,960 --> 00:11:17,679
A loss of reserve, a loss of morale,

184
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:21,159
a lot of, you know, loss of kind of well-being themselves

185
00:11:21,159 --> 00:11:24,139
and they might be struggling as adults.

186
00:11:24,639 --> 00:11:26,179
And if the parents are struggling,

187
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:29,360
it has obvious secondary effects on the kids, doesn't it?

188
00:11:29,360 --> 00:11:32,159
Because the parents and the peer group are the support system

189
00:11:32,159 --> 00:11:34,360
and the teachers, they're the support system

190
00:11:34,360 --> 00:11:36,539
for that young adult, emerging adult.

191
00:11:36,860 --> 00:11:39,480
And if the support system is struggling,

192
00:11:39,639 --> 00:11:41,419
then the young person will struggle too.

193
00:11:41,899 --> 00:11:45,220
And Pat, one of the things as parents that, you know,

194
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:48,639
a lot of us spend a lot of time, as you'd be aware,

195
00:11:48,720 --> 00:11:50,559
trying to manage screen time these days

196
00:11:50,559 --> 00:11:52,700
and make sure that your kids have enough balance.

197
00:11:52,740 --> 00:11:54,500
You've got to live with that world

198
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:56,340
and there are some benefits clearly to social media.

199
00:11:56,480 --> 00:11:57,879
It's a topic that's talked about regularly,

200
00:11:58,000 --> 00:11:59,379
but particularly in Melbourne,

201
00:11:59,480 --> 00:12:02,960
where you've had two years of training kids to a screen at homeschooling,

202
00:12:03,320 --> 00:12:05,720
you can just see that has become an even bigger issue

203
00:12:05,720 --> 00:12:07,980
for kids then to get them out connecting.

204
00:12:08,159 --> 00:12:09,639
And, you know, I use the word perfect storm,

205
00:12:09,759 --> 00:12:11,919
but for young teenage girls in particular

206
00:12:11,919 --> 00:12:14,639
and young boys seeing these unrealistic images on social media

207
00:12:14,639 --> 00:12:15,840
that, you know, they're not going to be able to get out of school.

208
00:12:15,840 --> 00:12:15,940
And I think that's a big issue.

209
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:17,100
They're bombarded with,

210
00:12:17,440 --> 00:12:19,720
without the connection of sport that's been taken away

211
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:21,240
and without all the things that keep them healthy,

212
00:12:21,320 --> 00:12:23,419
those intricate social catch-ups and connections

213
00:12:23,419 --> 00:12:26,200
that have been going, Pat, it's staggering.

214
00:12:26,320 --> 00:12:30,100
And for you to say you've got a thousand kids in your centres alone

215
00:12:30,100 --> 00:12:31,940
that can't access the help they need,

216
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:36,039
I mean, that's a stunning thing to me in such a developed city

217
00:12:36,039 --> 00:12:37,379
that we're not able to look after them.

218
00:12:37,460 --> 00:12:38,840
Pat, am I reading that the right way?

219
00:12:39,200 --> 00:12:39,740
Yeah, yeah.

220
00:12:39,820 --> 00:12:41,940
And I think, you know, we were lucky we've got a Premier

221
00:12:41,940 --> 00:12:44,539
and a Deputy Premier that recognised this

222
00:12:44,539 --> 00:12:45,940
and we had a health minister

223
00:12:45,960 --> 00:12:48,740
so Martin Foley, we had a Royal Commission

224
00:12:48,740 --> 00:12:52,139
which actually recognised the massive underinvestment

225
00:12:52,139 --> 00:12:53,919
in mental health care, especially in young people.

226
00:12:54,299 --> 00:12:58,080
So that is going to get fixed over the next few years.

227
00:12:58,179 --> 00:13:01,059
But right now, we've got a thousand young people,

228
00:13:01,440 --> 00:13:03,340
many of whom are in life-threatening situations

229
00:13:03,340 --> 00:13:04,740
that we can't help.

230
00:13:05,460 --> 00:13:08,059
Just imagine what that feels like for a mental health professional

231
00:13:08,059 --> 00:13:09,379
to be in that situation.

232
00:13:10,179 --> 00:13:12,179
It's as if, you know, with COVID,

233
00:13:12,440 --> 00:13:15,279
it's as if they had to turn away two out of three COVID cases

234
00:13:15,279 --> 00:13:15,940
who might die.

235
